{
  "answer": "**One specific procedural rule common to both texts concerns incompetent witnesses due to their inherent wickedness.** Both declare that thieves, perpetrators of violence (or \"violent men\"), and gamblers cannot serve as witnesses because truthfulness is absent in them.[^1][^2]\n\nNārada's operative line: \"Thieves, perpetrators of violence, the cruel, gamblers, and murderers are incompetent witnesses because of their wickedness; truth is not found in them.\" (Nar. 1.141)\n\nBṛhaspati's operative line: \"Thieves, violent men, eunuchs, gamblers, and informers—they are not witnesses due to their wickedness; testimony is not found in them.\" (Brh_1,5.3)\n\nBṛhaspati's version reads as a **clarification** of Nārada's: it preserves the core categories (thieves, violent men, gamblers) and rationale (wickedness precludes truthful testimony) while adding two further examples (eunuchs, informers) for precision without altering the principle.\n\n[^1]: Nārada Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-c37cca).\n\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-5a2654).",
